      "olympiad.g6.desc": "Master sophisticated mathematical modeling, complex graphical analysis, behavioral economics, and advanced econometric methods for top-level performance.",
      "olympiad.g7.desc": "Learn from frequent errors in conceptual understanding, calculations, time management, and develop systematic prevention strategies.",

      /* ── MICRO card body paragraphs ── */
      "micro.card.sd.body": "Demand slopes down because buyers usually want less at higher prices. Supply slopes up because higher prices make production more attractive. Equilibrium is where plans match. A price ceiling below equilibrium creates a shortage; a price floor above equilibrium creates a surplus.",
      "micro.card.el.body": "Elasticity measures responsiveness. Olympiad questions often ask whether total revenue rises or falls after a price change. If demand is elastic, price and revenue move in opposite directions; if inelastic, they move together.",
      "micro.card.ut.body": "Consumers allocate income until marginal utility per unit of money is equal across goods. The principle is not about perfect psychology; it is a clean model of trade-offs under constraints.",
      "micro.card.co.body": "Fixed costs do not change with output in the short run. Variable costs do. Marginal cost cuts average cost at its minimum. This one geometric fact explains many firm decisions.",
      "micro.card.ms.body": "Perfect competition has many price takers. Monopoly restricts output where marginal revenue equals marginal cost. Monopolistic competition adds differentiation. Oligopoly requires strategic reasoning.",
      "micro.card.gt.body": "Start with the payoff matrix. Check each player's best response for every rival action. A dominant strategy is best in all cases; Nash equilibrium is where no one wants to deviate alone.",
      "micro.card.oc.body": "Opportunity cost is the value of the next best alternative. It turns vague sacrifice into a measurable comparison and is the engine behind trade, specialization, and comparative advantage.",
      "micro.card.ca.body": "The producer with lower opportunity cost has comparative advantage. Even if one side is better at everything, both sides can gain from trade when relative costs differ.",

      /* ── MACRO card body paragraphs ── */
      "macro.card.gdp.p1": "Gross domestic product measures the market value of final goods and services produced inside a country during a period. The olympiad trap is to treat GDP as well-being. It is not. GDP misses leisure, informal work, environmental costs, and distribution, yet it remains powerful because it gives a common scale for output.",
      "macro.card.gdp.p2": "The expenditure identity is Y = C + I + G + (X - M). Consumption tracks household demand, investment tracks capital formation and inventories, government spending captures public purchases, and net exports adjust for foreign demand.",
      "macro.card.gdp.quote": "Key takeaway: GDP is a production measure, not a happiness measure. Always ask whether a change is nominal, real, final, or intermediate.",
      "macro.card.inf.p1": "Inflation is a sustained rise in the general price level. Students should separate a one-time price jump from continuing inflation. CPI follows a consumer basket, GDP deflator covers domestically produced output, and core measures remove volatile items to reveal trend pressure.",
      "macro.card.inf.p2": "Demand-pull inflation comes from excess spending; cost-push inflation comes from supply shocks; expected inflation can become self-fulfilling through wage and price setting.",
      "macro.card.unemp.p1": "Unemployment is not one thing. Frictional unemployment is search time, structural unemployment is skill or location mismatch, cyclical unemployment follows recessions, and natural unemployment remains even near potential output. Good analysis compares actual output with potential output and explains whether policy can help without overheating demand.",
      "macro.card.pol.p1": "Fiscal policy uses spending, taxes, and transfers. Expansionary fiscal policy can lift aggregate demand, but it may raise debt or crowd out investment when resources are already tight. Monetary policy changes interest rates, reserves, and expectations. Lower rates usually increase investment and consumption; higher rates cool inflation but can slow output.",
      "macro.card.ex.p1": "An appreciation makes imports cheaper and exports less competitive; a depreciation does the reverse. Exchange rates respond to interest differentials, inflation expectations, trade balances, and confidence. In small open-economy questions, always track both the goods market and capital flows.",
      "macro.card.islm.p1": "IS-LM is a short-run model of goods and money market equilibrium. IS shifts with fiscal policy, investment confidence, and net exports; LM shifts with money supply and liquidity preference. AD-AS then translates demand shocks and supply shocks into output and price-level outcomes.",
      "macro.card.islm.p2": "Diagram discipline matters: label axes, mark original equilibrium, show the shift, identify the new equilibrium, and write the economic story in one sentence.",
      "macro.card.gr.p1": "Long-run growth comes from labor, capital, human capital, technology, institutions, and productivity. Recessions occur when spending falls, financial conditions tighten, or supply is disrupted. Stabilization policy can reduce the pain, but sustainable growth requires capacity, not only stimulus.",

      /* ── ARTICLE: inflation ── */
      "art.inf.toc.title": "In this article",
